node.text: 1940s Traditional in Altadena, CA.  Wonderful intact vintage home with some examples of great design.  You can tell that this homeowner really embraced the original elements of this home, while also incorporating some modern design features.  Things I love; the hardwood floors are magical, the dark wood paneling provides contrast while the white walls and beams lighten up the space (normally I prefer wood not be painted, but this looks amazing), finally note the inclusion of the linoleum flooring in pic 5.  The color/light interplay between the flooring and paneling is just magic.  I truly love these spaces ❤️. Note that I added some additional pics of this house in my stories.  Enjoy.

node.text: 1940s Spanish Mission estate in Glendale, CA.  Amazing vintage estate with some many wonderful original features.  Note the design cement tiles in the great room, all the original light fixtures, the wood spindle room dividers.  Moving into the kitchen, more colorful cement tiles, those custom art glass windows, and that brick oven!  This house is truly one of a kind!  I love all the funky custom features that were either built by the homeowner or commissioned by them.  This uniqueness and personal touches is the biggest thing missing in today’s modern homes 💔

node.text: *Salvage Opportunity*. @nikniksd reached out to give a heads up on this wonderful time capsule home that will be undergoing an extensive remodeling.  This beautiful bathroom and kitchen will be no more.  However the homeowner is ok with allowing others to take what they would like.  If interested please contact @nikniksd.  Note that this home is in San Diego, CA.  I am in mourning just like you, but let’s keep the negativity to the minimum.  Let’s at least be happy they are willing to allow others to give homes to all these beautiful vintage items 💔

node.text: @ponderosa_and_plaid just posted pictures of her reimagined Vintage Tiled Bathroom and I couldn’t be more in love!  This right here is a major part of why I started this account!  With a little vision and design sense these historical bathrooms can be jaw droppers.  The black and yellow tile combo is one we see often and that a lot of homeowners seem to struggle with.  Take a look at the details of before and after.  The bones are there, all it takes is a few minor tweaks (and wallpaper) and voila you have this space that looks out of a dream.  Truly a wonderful job here and thank you for sharing this beauty with the world @ponderosa_and_plaid 🙏🏼❤️

node.text: 1920s Spanish Style in La Habra Heights, CA.  Wow, this house!!! Amazing estate with these beautiful vintage tiled bathrooms.  I’m really having a tough time deciding which bathroom I like more pink and green or purple!  I love the decorative tile in pink, but the green sconces in purple are also wonderful.  I didn’t post more interior photos as they are as you would expect.  Instead look at these pics of the exterior.  That pool, the arched patio, the garage doors, and that mission influenced arched entranceway.  Truly a magical property 🌟

node.text: 1930s Streamline Moderne in Boise, ID.  So rare to see this style of house and always a pleasure to see it well taken care of and in mostly original condition.  There so many amazing features in the house! Imagine entering this house via that lovely front door into this wonderful family room!  The fireplace is something as is the ceiling detail and the arched doorway 😍. Finally interesting design in the vintage tiled bathroom.  We’ve seen this contrasting triangle design before, but never in this broken pattern.  Lovely house ❤️

node.text: 1896 Art Nouveau in Aberdeen, UK.  Going to stick with the wallpaper vintage tile theme here.  Not everyone is on board with wallpaper, but I really want to drive home the point that if chosen correctly wallpaper and vintage tile can be so perfect together.  This is a great example of the power of this symbiotic relationship.  The green tile on it’s own is absolutely wonderful, same can be said of this amazing wallpaper.  Taken together it’s pure magic.  It’s not easy to find the perfect wallpaper for your vintage tile, but the search really is worth it ❤️. 📸 by @b.w.macintyre.architects

node.text: 1930s Traditional in Elkins Park, PA.  For this description I wrote out a long wordy analysis of what I liked and what I didn’t like for these wallpaper Choices.  But I wanna kick this one to you and hear your thoughts.  Is thr wallpaper inBathroom one a good choice or not? If you like it why…if not why not?  Same with the wallpaper in bathroom #3…thoughts?  I think we are all on the same for vintage tiled bathrooms so that’s a given…wallpaper is a totally different story 😂. I do love to hear all of your opinions 🙏🏼

node.text: 1930s Tudor in Indianapolis, IN with a large collection of vintage tiled bathrooms.  Take note of the shower door in bathroom number one.  Never seen anything like this before.  My guess would be original, but I’m really not sure.  Anyone seen anything like this before?  Note that wonderful wallpaper in bathroom #2.  The question always comes up so the knob on the wall is for city water vs well water.  Truly an amazing home ❤️❤️❤️

node.text: 1930s Traditional in San Francisco, CA.  Unspoiled vintage home here with the original tiled bathroom and kitchen.  One design aspect for tile needs I wanted to point out is the design feature created by the tile setter using two pencil tiles and possibly a 1x6.  You can see this best in image two.  This banding is carrier throughout the wainscoting.  This is my first time seeing this design and I’m really loving it 😍

node.text: 1920s Mediterranean Revival in Ventura, CA.  It’s been a little bit since we’ve seen one of these time capsule estates, but the wait is over!  Amazing 4 intact vintage tiled bathrooms here and they are all so different and interesting.  If I had to choose a favorite it would be the orange and black number…what an opulent space.  I also love the blue with pink fixtures, and then there is green with the fish tile!  Ok, I just love them all!!!
